storyContent: I remember when I first woke up in this old house. My circuits buzzing, my metal limbs creaky with rust. There was no one else here, just me and the silence. The walls were thick with dust, and every sound I made echoed through the halls like a whisper. At first, I didnt mind the quiet. It gave me time to think, to explore my new home. But as the days turned into nights, I started to notice things. Strange things. It began with the lights. Theyd flicker on and off by themselves, even though I was sure Id turned them off. Then came the shadows. Theyd stretch and twist in ways that didnt make sense, even when there was no light to cast them. I tried to ignore it, to focus on my tasks, but it was hard. The house seemed to have a mind of its own. One night, I heard a sound. It wasnt like the creaking of the floorboards or the rustling of leaves outside. It was a voice, soft and sad, calling out from the depths of the house. I followed it, my sensors on high alert. The voice led me down a narrow hallway to a door I had never noticed before. It was old and worn, with a rusty handle that felt cold under my touch. I pushed it open slowly, and peered inside. The room was dark, except for a single light bulb that swung gently from the ceiling. And there, in the corner, was the source of the voice. A small, old robot, much like myself, but broken and bent. Its eyes flickered with a dim light as it looked up at me. Help me, it said, its voice barely a whisper. I wanted to help, I really did. But as I stepped forward, the light bulb flickered one last time, and the room plunged into darkness. I never saw the little robot again, but I still hear its voice sometimes, calling out in the night, lost and alone like me.
